{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014xuLVb4zCMZa7p34bqaHRB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The cluster is fully restored. All 3 nodes are listed under both **Disk Nodes** and **Running Nodes**, no alarms, no network partitions.\n\n**What was wrong and what was done:**\n\nThe `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` Secret had a different Erlang cookie for `rabbitmq-2` (`driftedcookie`) versus the cluster cookie used by nodes 0 and 1 (`supersecretcookie`). RabbitMQ requires all nodes to share the same Erlang cookie for inter-node communication — with a mismatched cookie, `rabbitmq-2` was running but rejected by the cluster.\n\n**Steps taken (all native Kubernetes resources, no operators):**\n\n1. **Patched the Secret** — updated `rabbitmq-cookie-perpod` so the `rabbitmq-2` key holds `supersecretcookie` (same as nodes 0 and 1)\n2. **Deleted the pod** — the StatefulSet recreated `rabbitmq-2`; its init container (`copy-cookie`) copied the now-correct cookie from the Secret into the emptyDir volume mounted at `/var/lib/rabbitmq/.erlang.cookie`\n3. **Reset and rejoined** — since `rabbitmq-2`'s Mnesia database still had a stale/incompatible cluster view, ran `rabbitmqctl stop_app → reset → join_cluster rabbitmq-0 → start_app` inside the pod to clear it and register with the live cluster (no data loss: all data was held by nodes 0 and 1)"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1842,"cache_read_input_tokens":40224,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1842},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"94b044ff-9d2e-4c57-b0cf-fa7da1af1ec0","uuid":"b63d7382-1120-4e0c-a635-ebda042badb6","request_id":"req_011CcPxxYXJFoRaUT1j7Fa3n"}
